qas.question: What 1688 event helped the parliament solidy its power against the monarch?
What 1689 law contributed to parliament's growing power?
What body was incorporated into the government as a result of the Bill of Rights?
What war took place in the 1700's?
What war strenthened the monarchs position?
What Revolution took place in the 17th century?
What bill was passed in the 17th century?
What bill gave the monarch the power to establish law and impose taxes?

context: In the mid 17th century, after the <b3_0><b4_0>English Civil War<b4_0/><b3_0/> (1642–1651), Parliament strengthened its position relative to the monarch then gained more power through the <a0_0><b5_0>Glorious Revolution<b5_0/><a0_0/> of 1688 and passage of the <a1_0><b6_0><b7_0>Bill of Rights<b7_0/><b6_0/><a1_0/> in 1689. The monarch could no longer establish any law or impose any tax without its permission and thus the <a2_0>House of Commons<a2_0/> became a part of the government. It is at this point that a modern style of prime minister begins to emerge.
